  </p>

  <h2>Implementation Tips for Travel CRM Success</h2>

  <h3>1. Clean Up Your Existing Data</h3>
  <p>
    Before migrating to a new CRM, clean up your customer data. Remove duplicates, update 
    outdated information, and standardize formatting.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Define Your Sales Stages</h3>
  <p>
    Map out your typical sales process and configure your CRM pipeline to match. Common 
    stages for travel include: New Inquiry → Qualified → Proposal Sent → Negotiation → 
    Booking Confirmed → Lost.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Train Your Team</h3>
  <p>
    A CRM is only as good as its adoption rate. Invest time in training your team and 
    emphasize the benefits they'll experience.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Set Up Automation Gradually</h3>
  <p>
    Don't try to automate everything at once. Start with simple follow-up reminders, 
    then gradually add more sophisticated sequences.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Review and Refine</h3>
  <p>
    Regularly review your CRM data to identify patterns and opportunities for improvement. 
    Which lead sources convert best? Where do leads stall in your pipeline?
  </p>

